Every December I do a lot of reflecting on the year. What worked. What didn’t work. Where I want to focused my attention. And what I can learn from the previous year.

2022 ended up being a big year of transition for me as I started a new job and went back to 9-5 life for the first time in 6+ years.

I am grateful for all this year has taught me, especially how the magic happens when I’m my most authentic, unfiltered, real self.

How about you, did you learn any big lessons this year?

There is something so delightful about going into a book knowing you’re going to love it. And that’s me with a  @christinalauren book 📚

This book is a great follow-up to The Soulmate Equation focusing on Jess’ best friend, Fizzy.

You can’t NOT love Fizzy, a beloved romance novelist with a passionate fan base. This book has a swoony British love interest. Dual points of view. A reality tv dating show. A bit of steam. And a bit of forbidden romance.

With the main character being a romance writer, I loved the nods to various tropes and archetypes throughout.

The True Love Experiment comes out May 16… my birthday which I obviously have to point out 😂 Be sure to preorder it as this will be the perfect beach read for summer.

Thank you @gallerybooks for my advanced copy 💗

✨ Let me know in the comments if you’ve read any @christinalauren books and if so what your fave is ✨

I *think* I’ve finally narrowed down my own word of the year for 2023 😉 but I’ll actually be sitting down to answer these questions for myself later tonight to make sure it’s the right fit for this year.

I love making a vision board at the beginning of every year. 

I go in with a few ideas of things I want to look for. There might be some clues for what I think is going to be my word of the year 😏

I also had a few things I wanted to include that I want to happen this year:
🌊 a beach resort vacation
😂 hopefully another harry styles concert
🛁 a new bathroom

Here’s a mini review of everything I read in December:

Gift From the Sea - I had never heard of this book but it’s one of my moms all time favorites and she gave it to me for Chanukah. It’s the perfect little book of essays reflecting on life, solitude, and reconnecting with your core. 10/10 would recommend.
📚
Before I Let Go - A beautiful and achingly painful romance between a divorced couple who has gone through and awful loss together. Romances can be hit miss for me these days but this one is such a hit with it’s complex characters.
CW: Still birth and suicide ideation.
📚
Kiss Her Once For Me: A delightfully cozy sapphic romance that takes place over the holidays with a fake engagement, second chance romance, and a family you’ll absolutely fall in love with. Pairs well with a warm chai latte.
📚
Just By Looking at Him - Messy, hilarious, and a bit of a roller coaster. Follows a successful tv writer who can’t stop cheating on his boyfriend and how his cerebral palsy has him feeling like
"gay shrek" (the books words, not mine). Wasn’t plot heavy enough for me and almost read like non-fiction vignettes but I like where it went in the end.
📚
The True Love Experiment (comes out 5/16) - There is nothing more comforting to me than a Christina Lauren book and this one is no exception. Follows Fizzy (from The Soulmate Equation) as she gets cast on a bachelorette-type show but ends to falling for the dreamy producer. I can’t wait for you to read this book when it comes out!
✨
I’d love to hear from you: what’s your favorite book you’ve recently read?

Here’s everything I read in January 📚 I’ve been in a bit of a reading slump and DNF’d a ton of books this month, so this is what i actually finished 😂

I’d love to hear from you in the comments: let me know your favorite book you read in January 💗

THE REUNION: I adored this second chance romance between the former stars of a popular teen show. I’m such a sucker of a Hollywood romance and loved the gossip blog posts throughout. One of my favorite romances I’ve read recently.

ARE YOU THERE GOD…: I wanted to reread this iconic book before the movie comes out — I must’ve first read this book over 20 years ago when I was a pre-teen! After all these years I still love Judy Blume’s ability to convey what it feels like to be 12 but without a hint of judgement towards the character. This wasn’t my absolute favorite of hers growing up (I remember loving Sally J. Friedman + Just as Long As We’re Together) so I’d be curious to reread some of my other Judy faves from growing up.

WOMAN OF THE YEAR (comes out 3/21): I devoured this wild ride of a revenge book. 20 years ago Lorelei and Holly were best friends at college… until they had a falling out. Now Lorelei is seeking revenge on Holly for what happened… but she might be in danger too. It reminded me a bit of Luckiest Girl Alive as we find out what happened in the past. It’s a bit twisted so I’d skip if that isn’t for you!

LESSONS IN CHEMISTRY: I know this is a favorite for many… but it just wasn’t for me. We follow Elizabeth Zott through what it’s like to be a woman chemist in the 1960s, and how she eventually becomes the unlikely host of a cooking show. I found the beginning to be a major slog and kind of hated her love interest which made it hard to get invested. I liked the second half a bit more but still just felt meh about the whole book. I know so many people that love this book though so maybe that’s just me?

Books that broke my heart 💔😭 (but in the best kind of way) 

Have you read any of these books? Any you would add to the list? 📚

One of my favorite things about getting older has been shamelessly loving the things I love.

Growing up I felt so embarrassed by my passion for theater in a town that was hyper-focused on sports.

In college I felt so much shame for loving cheesy musicals in a theater program that was honestly kind of pretentious.

Now? I’m going to love what I love. Cheesy musical theater, Harry Styles, One Direction, the color pink, books that are just plain fun. 

I love what I love. And will do it shamelessly 💗

A few years ago I decided to make this list. My simple self-care checklist as I think of it. A list of simple things I can do when I’m in a funk or not feeling like my best self.

It’s nothing ground breaking. But remembering to go for a walk, even if it’s quick, or text someone I love that I’m thinking about them? Can surprisingly turn the day around for me.

My life isn’t exactly where I thought I’d be in my 30s.

I thought i’d be married by now.
I thought I’d feel a lot more settled.
I thought I’d feel older
And I definitely thought I’d feel like less of a mess.

But I am slowly working on letting go of this expectation of what my life “should” look like in my early 30s. I’m learning to embrace, enjoy, and savor what it *actually* looks like. 

Even if it’s not quite what I pictured 💗

THIS BOOK 😭💗📚 Every once in awhile I’ll read a book that just absolutely consumes me. A book I’ll both want to savor so it never ends but also devour so I can let it take over my whole weekend. Adelaide was one of those books for me. 

Adelaide, an 26 year old American grad school living in London, loves fiercely. Rory, a handsome, charming, Englishman she starts dating, is the opposite.

We meet Adelaide at her rock bottom and see what exactly played out to get her there. 

This book is eerily relatable for many of us. There were moments that I swear were pulled from the journals I kept as a teen and 20-something. It’s raw. Devastating. Heartbreaking. But wow was it also so full of truth.

I’m saying this now: this book will be THE book this spring. Go preorder it now and thank yourself April 18… and bonus points if you do so on @bookshop_org 😉

I’ve been (understandably) hit with a wave of grief + nostalgia this week.

✨ BOOK REVIEW ✨
Happy Place by @emilyhenrywrites 
Comes out April 25

📚 WHAT’S IT ABOUT? 📚
Harriet and Wyn broke up 5 months ago. But no one in their life knows. Now they’re stuck on a vacation together with their close group of friends pretending to still be together.

💭 MY THOUGHTS 💭
Oh, this book. If you’re looking for a light and fun rom com, this ain’t it. But if you’re in the mood for a romance with big emotions that will gut you, this is for you.

I read a lot of romance but even so can sometimes find the genre too saccharine and fake. As a romance centered around a break up this felt so much more grounded and rooted in reality.

The book is raw and tender in how it talks about the complexities of break-ups. I found myself sobbing at various points from quotes that just felt so damn relatable.

💗 WHAT I LOVED 💗
• Refreshing take on romance and fake dating trope
•Sub plot about how friendships change in your 30s
•Harriet as a main characters. She’s brilliant and kind yet has her own flaws and insecurities
•The commentary on break-ups from long-time relationships and aftermath

🤷‍♀️ WHAT I DIDN’T LOVE 🤷‍♀️
•This is a me thing BUT… some of the lines and language just made my skin crawl. There would be a random erotic line about nipples in the middle of nowhere.
•The resolution felt very simple for how big the problem felt

👇🏻 ALL IN ALL 👇🏻
I officially have a new favorite Emily Henry book 😭 I’m so excited for you to read it and be crushed by it too.

RATING: ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️💫

Anyone else terrible at celebrating their wins?

I had a big work win this week. Within minutes of the good news I found myself already thinking: okay, let’s conquer the next big goal and get to the next big thing.

I hadn’t given myself even 5 minutes to celebrate the win before I was already onto the next thing 🤦‍♀️

I’m working on finding that balance of yes, wanting to continue to grow and do more and hit that next goal, but also be able to celebrate and even just acknowledge the wins along the way.

✨ BOOK REVIEW ✨
Meet Me at the Lake by @carleyfortune 

📚 WHAT’S IT ABOUT? 📚
10 years ago, Fern and Will spent one day together in Toronto that totally transforms both of them. They make a pact: Meet back up in 1 year at the lakeside resort Fern’s family owns Flash forward 10 years and Fern is mourning the loss of her mother at their resort. Will never showed up to their promised reunion, but for some reason he’s at the resort now after all these years…

💭 MY THOUGHTS 💭
Carley Fortune writes romances that make my heart ache but are also so much more than a romance. This is a story of family, and chosen family, and grief, and growing up. It’s about change both by choice but also when it’s forced upon us.

I’d describe this book as a “rom” rather than a “rom com” which I’m realizing is my romance of choice. 

In the end I was crying because I didn’t want it to be over. I didn’t want to wait for another Carley Fortune book and I wished every book I read make me feel like this. 

💗 WHAT I LOVED 💗
• the Dirty Dancing resort vibes
• how Fern’s story was woven in with her mom’s story
• it’s a romance but also so much more than a love story
•both timelines: I found myself excited to live in both worlds
•everything about the writing. It’s swoon-y and honest but *never* cringey or cheesy 

👇🏻 ALL IN ALL 👇🏻
Carley Fortune’s done it again. If you read and loved EVERY SUMMER AFTER like I did, I challenge you to approach this one with an open mind and fresh eyes. There are similarities, sure, but they are definitely different but beautiful beasts.

And if you need me, I’ll be nursing a book hangover for the next few days 😭

Drag shows, and besties, and pool season, and aunting, and London, and Harry Styles, and hearing Sweet Creature live, and launching the biggest project of my career 1 day after getting back from London 🤪

I found myself scrolling on social media last night comparing my long weekend to all of those ones that I was seeing all over my feed. 

I was filled with this icky feeling of envy as I compared my life to what I was seeing. Why didn’t MY long weekend look like that!?

It’s silly to say, but suddenly I forgot about my own long weekend 🤦‍♀️ The one that I also shared the highlight reel of on social media. One that maybe other people were *also* playing the comparison game with.

It’s so easy on social media to feel like we’re missing out. To watch the highlight reel of someone else’s life and feel like everyone else is living this incredible life, be it in Italy, at the beach, with a significant other, or whatever it is. We compare it to our real life, the real feelings and messy moments, and of course the curated life someone else is sharing seems better. Why wouldn’t it!?

TLDR: Stop comparing your real life to someone else’s social media highlight reel. Especially so in the summer…

I’m not usual one for holiday books… or really anything holiday-y. But this book totally won this grinch over — which is saying a lot as I read it during a heatwave this summer.

It’s a holiday book. It has some romance. It’s very New York. But what I especially loved about it is that it’s really a love story about a group of friends.

I could especially relate to the platonic love between the two leads, a straight female and gay male. It’s a dynamic near and dear to my heart.

It’s also for us 30-something’s that are starting to feel a real shift in our friendships as we get older and our lives start to change.

Sometimes I cry at the end of a book because I loved it so much. And this was one of those books for me. Now go read this book!

A question I get asked a lot is if I miss teaching yoga and fitness.

And the truthful answer is yes but no.

Before the pandemic teaching was my life. I felt so much pride in what I did. I felt so proud of myself for making that dream come true. I also felt exhausted trying to keep up with my 16 classes a week schedule and 6AM classes.

I love where my career has taken me and the changes I was forced to make because of the pandemic. I have a better sense of work life balance. I love what I do. It’s pretty sweet to have PTO and health insurance…

But sometimes? I’m still hit with a wave of sadness and grief for my life pre-March 2020. I find myself wondering what would have happened if the pandemic didn’t cause so much damage to my old industry.

Both can be true 💗

Because this message is worth sharing every year — 

This is your yearly reminder to not use phrases like "burn off your Turkey" or "earn your stuffing" this week (and of course similar phrases all year round)

As a former fitness instructor + yoga teacher I know how easy it is to just spout things like this out. But I also know we can do better than this.
Instead let's focus on uplifting our clients. Maybe your class is the only 45 minutes they'll have this week to focus on themselves. Maybe your class is helping them manage the anxiety of dealing with family. Maybe your class is the only time they will spend in a community if they aren't able to be with family for wherever reason.

Use this as a chance to lift your clients up, not bring them down 💗

When I first moved to New York City, at the ripe young age of 18, I quickly learned how to take solace in my own company. 

I’d go to Broadway shows alone in college when none of my other friends wanted to see the shows I wanted to see. I’d go for solo lunch dates at the Thai restaurant on 8th street that had an amazing lunch special. I’d go on solo adventures around the city just because.

I am really good at being alone. Maybe too good at times as I’ll often choose my own company over feeling social awkward in a situation. But as I’ve grown older I’ve come to realize that this is a skill that I am proud to possess.

Being alone and lonely are not the same. And learning to love my alone time has been so powerful for me 💗

In 2011, I started a blog and sharing bits and pieces of my life on the internet because I was feeling alone. I wanted to connect with people who were passionate about the same things as I was… which at the time was fitness.

Starting that blog led to sharing on this *here* channel. It led to meeting some of my closest friends. It led to my career as a social media manager. And it’s led to countless incredible opportunities. 

In the last 12 years, my content has evolved and shifted. Fitness is no longer my main focus. But the core of *why* I share has remained the same: To make people feel less alone.

I’m really bad at celebrating the wins. There is a part of me that feels cringy even sharing this post. I am tempted to just brush this off as nothing. But fuck it, I am going to take this moment to celebrate. 

Whether you’ve been here since the early Kayla in the City days or are new here, thank you for your support and for being part of this community. I am beyond grateful to each and every one of you 💗

i’ve been making a yearly vision board since 2015 and it’s one of my favorite rituals. everyone has their favorite method and preferred medium but for me, I just love turning it into a little arts and crafts project. 

i don’t think too hard about it — i’ll flip through magazines and cut out what stands out to me. sometimes there’s things I know I *want* to include as they will be a big focus for the year (like all those years I was apartment hunting and had a photo of a washer dryer…) But honestly? I just cut out what feels right. it always ends up being just what i need 💗

In my recent Q+A I got a lot of questions about my career transition.

In April 2022 I went back to a 9-5 job after teaching yoga + fitness as my main gig. Before the pandemic I was teaching 16 classes a week and juuust about making the same salary as at my previous entry level marketing position.

I loved teaching. So much. But when studios reopened, it just became impossible. My pay was slashed. I was working longer hours for less money. I was so exhausted I couldn’t fathom picking up more classes. Something had to change.

It was a really emotional change for me. I felt like I had failed when really the industry had failed me. And so many other instructors.

The obvious choice was going back to social media marketing. Before focusing on teaching full-time I worked in social media at various fitness start ups and also went to business school and got my masters degree in social media marketing.

I had kept up my own social media presence and was doing some social media coaching at the time so I was pretty up on the current state of social media. 

I targeted the book world as that had become something I was passionate about and ended up applying for the right social media role at the right time at Bookshop.org, an Amazon alternative for buying books online that supports indie bookstores.

As I type this up I’m packing for a 2 week trip to LA. I am taking it fully off work and I’m still perplexed by the idea of paid time off. What a concept 😂 I didn’t have to teach extra classes or beg people to sub for me.

For me, going back to a 9-5 job was the right choice 💗
